11. Datatypes: 
- int, float, double, char, boolean, short, byte, long -> PRIMITIVE DTYPES
- classes, strings, arrays -> NON - PRIMITIVE DTYPES
- String is a NON-PRIMITIVE dtype - because we make its object and then call its different methods. 
- Primitive ones stores values directly whereas non-primitive ones stores references/addresses.
Like Arrays stores actual values in heap memory and address [0] in stack memory.
- Range -> byte < short < int < long 
- float - 7.8 decimals 
- double - 15.16 decimals 
- End the value with an "f" for floats and "d" for doubles. 
- float f1 = 35e3f; // 35000 
- boolean - true/false
- char - single quotes - ASCII value - A to Z (65-90) - a to z (97-122) 
- var - automatically identifies the dtype...but we cant change stype once allocated. 
- Narrow Casting (big to small) -> manually (dtype)..
- Widening Casting (small to big) -> automatically... no loss of data...
- byte < short < char < int < long < float < double. 

12. Operators: 
- Arithmetic Operators:  + - * / % ++ --  (10/3 = 3)
    -> ++ -- works for int, char, byte, float, double, short. <NOT BOOLEAN>
- Assigment: = += -= *= /= %= &= |= <<= >>= ^=
- Comparison/Relational: == > < >= <= != 
- Logical: && || ! (true -> false / false -> true)
- Bitwise: & | >> << ~ (flips bits) ^ (same 0 alag 1) >>> 
    -> >> (right shift):- positive then aage 1 else 0 
    -> >>> (zero right shift):- always aage 0 
- instanceof operator:- used for ref var like is a relationship. checks 'abc' ref var is actually of this dtype or not => returns true/false
- Precedence: 
  () [] .    POSTFIX OPERATORS
  ++ -- + - (unary wala -> y = -x) ~ !  UNARY OPERATOR (r - l associativity)
  *, /, %
  +, - 
  >> << >>> 
  >, <, >=, <=, instanceof 
  ==, != 
  & 
  ^ 
  | 
  && 
  || 
  ?: TERNARY (r - l associativity)
  = += -= *= /= %= &= ^= |= <<= >>= >>>= ASSIGNMENT (r - l associativity)

13. Conditionals: 
