- CONSTRUCTOR: 
    - object created and its gets automatically called.  
    - matches name as class. 
    - no return type 
    - TYPES:  
        - NO-ARGS => nothing is passed.
        - DEFAULT => not created in class.  
        - PARAMETERISED => Params are passed. 
    - Constructor Overloading => same name, different args, (return type doesnt matter)

- INHERITENCE: 
    - BASIC IDEA: 
        - reusing the functionalities of an existing class in a new class.
        - Existing class - parent class / base class 
        - New class - child class / derived class
        - Child class will inherit all data members and member functions of parent class. 
        - Even nested classes too. 
        - BUT Not constructors... 
        - Follows IS-A relationship. 
        - class Person {
    
        } 
          class Student extends Person{
    
        }
        - extends → class inherits from class (class → class inheritance)
        - implements → class inherits from interface (interface → class inheritance)

    - PARENT REF VAR and SUBCLS OBJECT: 
        - Subclass object contains - uske DM + MFs  and  Parent DMs and MFs. 
        - Parent cls ref variable can hold Child class object. 
            - However, we can only access - parent class DM + MFs only. 
            - To access both, we have to use subclass reference variable. 
    
    - super() 
        - It is used to invoke parent class constructor. 
        - Differentiate members of super class and sub class. 
        - Suppose there's a method called display() which is overridden, we can use super.display() from subclass => IT WILL CALL THE PARENT METHOD NOT THE OVER-RIDDEN ONE. 
        - super.x / super.display() -> dono we can use. 
        - Suppose if there is a <constructor-overloading> in the parent class and we have called super(), then it will call the constructor based on the parameters which is passed. - IT SHOULD BE THE FIRST LINE.
    
    - extends vs implements: 
        - extends used by -> (to inherit props & behav of)  [class - class / interface - interface]. 
        - implements used by CLASS to inherit props and behavs of INTERFACE.
        - IMPLEMENTS and EXTENDS normally follow IS-A relationship. 
    
    - instanceof operator is used to find whether subclass is actually an instance of super class. 
        - returns true if yes else false.

    - IMPORTANT: 
            class Rohu {
                int x = 10;
            }

            class Machlii extends Rohu {
                int x = 20;
            }

            Rohu obj = new Machlii();
            System.out.println(obj.x);

        - Here obj.x prints 10 and not 20. due to COMPILE TIME BINDING. 

        - WHAT HAPPENED IN THE ENTIRE FLOW???
        - COMPILE TIME: (javac ....java)
            - Sara syntax check kiya
            - Reference based checks kiya - like ye method call ho sakta hai ya ni, ye field we can access or not. 
            - Binding -> obj.x binded with Rohu.x 
                - Doesnt decide for methods now. 
            - If compilation is successful, then BYTECODE IS generated. (.class file generated.)
        - CLASS LOADING: (Java Main)
            - Reads and loads both class files. 
            - Abhi tak ka info: JVM has dono class ka naam, unke field & method lists, uska constructor and access modifers ka info. 
            - Initially Rohu cls load hua...layout banega....(object mai konsi field kiske bad store hogi uski layout)
              CLASS LAYOUT: 
              Rohu.x -> offset 0 
            - Fir Machhli cls load hua uska layout bana...(object mai konsi field kiske bad store hogi uski layout)
              CLASS LAYOUT: 
              Rohu.x -> offset 0 
              Machliii.x -> offset 4 
            - Dono alag hai...no override...
        - LINKING: 
            - Verification -> for any illegal access. 
            - Static vars are assigned with memory. 
            - Resolution -> obj.x - Rohu.x (decided during Compile time) -> ab usse address/offset miljayega.
        - INITIALIZATION:
            - static vars are assigned with values. 
            - static objects are created. 
        - RUNTIME: 
            - Object bana. 
            - Use mem allocate huiii
            - Instance var will be assigned memory with default values. 
            - Instance vars are initialised. 
            - Rohu const call hua. 
            - Machliii const call hua. 
            - Methods call hogaa. 
    
    - IMPORTANT: 
            - public class Rohu{
                int x; 
                public Rohu(){
                    x = 40;
                }

                public void getRohu(){
                    System.out.println("Udta fire dil sambhalna jane naa!!"); 
                }
            }

            class Machlii extends Rohu{
                int y; 
                Machlii(){
                    y = 45;
                }
                public void getMaachhaah(){
                    System.out.println("Ude dil befikreeee"); 
                }
            } 

            public class Main{
                public static void main(String[] args){
                    Rohu obj = new Machlii(); 
                    System.out.println(obj.x); 
                    obj.getRohu(); 

                    Machlii obj2 = new Machlii();
                    System.out.println(obj2.x); 
                    System.out.println(obj2.y); 
                    obj2.getMaachhaah(); 
                    obj2.getRohu();
                }
            }
    
        -  We made an Machliii object. So how its calling Rohu Constuctor and getting x = 40.??
        - JVM sees Machliii ka object banana hai. but child cannot exist without parent class. So it automatically calls super() and invokes the parent cls constructor. and then child cls constructor will be called.
        - HOW THE FLOW HAPPENS??
            - Memory allocated 
               x = 0   y = 0 
            - JVM calls super() 
            - x = 40 (by Rohu() constructor) 
            - y = 45 (by Machliii() constructor) 
        - WHY THEN Machliii object cannot call getMachhah() ???
        - Initially during compilation, Compiler checks just the reference type. which was ROHU. and doesnt bother to see the object. 
        - Thinks its an object of ROHU cls. and thus it gives a compilation error when we can getMachhah() as its a method for Machliii cls. 
        - Once it gets compiled properly, then we move towards runtime. 
        - In runtime, we check whether the particular method is overridden or not. If it is we will call the child method else parent one. 
        - WHY child?? "object ka real behav child define karta hai than parent." 
        - BUT this happens only in case of Methods (RUNTIME BINDING HAPPENS HERE...)

    - TYPES OF INHERITENCE: 
        - SINGLE -> B extends A
        - MULTILVL -> B extends A and C extends B....
        - HIERARCHICAL -> B extends A and C extends A....
        - MULTIPLE -> B,C extends A ❌❌ (((not in java...)))
            - Solution was: to use interfaces to achieve this. 
    [CODE-CHECKOUT-----experiments/pillars_of_oops/inheritence]


- AGGREGATION:- 
    - Relationship between two classes where one class contains an instance of another class. 
    - Follows HAS-A Relationship. 
    - WHY NEEDED ?? Code reusability. 
    [CODE-CHECKOUT-----experiments/pillars_of_oops/aggregation]

- POLYMORPHISM: 
    - Ability to take on multiple forms (show different behav) based on situations. Can be an object or a method. 
    - Eg: Animal p = new cat(); 
        p = new dog(); 
        - Reference variable same hi hai (Animal p) but usne jis object ka reference store kiya hai wo alag alag hai. 
        - Based on situation, isne bhi apna behav/form badal diya. 
    - Any JAVA objects with more than 1 IS-A relationship is considered to be <polymorphic>. 
    - All JAVA objects are polymorphic. 
        - cat IS A cat. 
        - cat IS A object. 
        - These two are fixed for every object. 

    - REFERENCE VARIABLE: 
        - Cannot change the type of reference variable once assigned. 
        - Can point to any object of its cls type or its subcls type. 
        - Can be of a class or an interface. 
        - Defines what we can access. 

    - TYPES OF POLYMORPHISM:
        - Compile time polymorphism / Static Polymorphism 
            - performed by [method-overloading]
        - Run time polymorphism / Dynamic Polymorphism 
            - performed by [method-overriding]

    - Virtual Method -> Wo methods jo runtime pe call hote hain based on object type are virtual methods.

    - OVERRIDING: 
        - means to override the functionality of an existing method. 
        - WHY NEEDED ?? to define a behav specific to child cls. 
        - WHILE OVERRIDING, we can have:
            - different access modifers - provided child cls AM has [equal-or-more] visibility. 
            - different return types - provided child cls return type follows [is-a] relationship with return type of parent. 
            - NO, we need to have <same> [list-of-paramters].
        - TWO PRIMARY CONDITIONS FOR OVERRIDDING: 
            - method is inherited to child cls. 
            - Redefined by child cls.
        - static methods are not overridden 
            - they belong to class not object. settled during the compile time itself. 
            - no requirement of object to call those methods. 
            - parent and child can have same name static methods. BASED ON REFERENCE TYPE - will be decided in COMPILE TIME BINDING itself, that which method will be called.
        - While overridding, both methods have to be [non-static]. Koi bhi ek static hogya -> ERROR.
        - If we mark a method as [final], then we cannot override it. 
            - But we can call the parent one still.
        - If we mark a method as [private], then we cannot override it. 
            - Also we cannot call the parent method -> NO VISIBILITY due to PRIVATE AM. 
        - CONSTRUCTOR cannot be overridden. 
            - [WHY??] -> because it is not inherited. 
        - Use @Override
            - Performs compile time error checks. 
            - Catches bugs early.
        [CODE-CHECKOUT-----experiments/pillars_of_oops/polymorphism]

    - METHOD OVERLOADING: 
        - two or more methods with same METHOD NAME but with different params, is METHOD OVERLOADING. 
        - OVERLOADING = same name + diff params list. 
        - Return type, Access Modifier, static/non-static doesn't matter. 
        [CODE-CHECKOUT-----experiments/pillars_of_oops/polymorphism]

    - DYNAMIC BINDING: 
        - Process in which linking between METHOD CALL and METHOD IMPLEMENTATION is solved at runtime is called as DYNAMIC BINDING. 
        - Late Binding 
        - Decided based on type of objects not reference type. 
        - ALL Virtual methods performs DYNAMIC BINDING. 
        - if super keyword is used inside child class non static method - it calls parent ones. 
        [CODE-CHECKOUT-----experiments/pillars_of_oops/polymorphism/overriding] 
    
    - STATIC BINDING: 
        - Process in which linking between METHOD CALL and METHOD IMPLEMENTATION is solved at compile time is called as STATIC BINDING. 
        - Early Binding 
        - Static/Final/Private methods - decided during compile time. 
        - Decided based on type of reference not object type. 
        - Method Overloading is STATIC BINDING. 
            - Compile time mai hi usne signature match kiya and link kardiya.
        [CODE-CHECKOUT-----experiments/pillars_of_oops/polymorphism/overloading] 
    
    - INSTANCE INITIALIZER BLOCK:
        - Block declared inside a class to declare data members
        - Executed once per object. 
        - Executed before constructor call. 
        - public class Tester {
            public int a;
            { 
                a = 10; 
            }   
            Tester(){
                a = 20;
            }
        }
            - Initialised as 10 due to IIB then got overridden by constructor (20). 

        - In case of child class, first parent constructor is called, then IIB, then child constructor.

- ABSTRACT CLASSES: 
    - [abstract] keyword is used to achieve this. 
    - WHAT IT CAN HAVE??
        - Abstract methods 
        - Concrete Methods (with implementation/body)
        - Constructors 
        - Static vars and methods.
        - Final methods (concrete ones) 
        - Instance vars. 
    - WHAT IT CANNOT HAVE?
        - Cannot be declared final 
            - [WHY??] because we need abstract classes to be extended to be of any use. final restricts it. 
        - Instance cannot be created. 
            - [WHY??] because it may/maynot have implementations of many methods. 
        - Cannot be declared private 
            - [WHY??] No visibility outside the same abstract class, so cant extend it. 
    - ABSTRACT METHOD: 
        - In any class, if there is even one abstract method, then it has to be declared as an abstract class. 
        - Class extending abstract class should provide implementation of all abstract methods. 
        - ABSTRACT METHOD -> abstract void show(); -> methods without body.
        - Any class inheriting the current class must either override the abstract method or declare itself as abstract.  [CODE-CHECKOUT-----experiments/pillars_of_oops/abstraction/special.java]
    [CODE-CHECKOUT-----experiments/pillars_of_oops/abstraction/abstract_class.java] 
        
- ABSTRACTION: 
    - Hiding the implementation details from users, only functionality will be provided. 
    - Users know what it does -- not how it does?
    - Achieved by using ABSTRACT CLASSES and INTERFACES. 
    [CODE-CHECKOUT-----experiments/pillars_of_oops/abstraction/abstract_class.java] 

- INTERFACES: 
    - WHAT IT CAN HAVE??
        - Abstract methods ✅ (by default all are abstract)
        - Concrete Methods ✅ (use default keyword.)
        - Constructors ❌
        - Static vars. ✅ (by default vars are static)
        - static methods. ✅ 
        - Final methods ❌
        - Instance vars. ❌
    - Method Body exists -> static methods and default methods. 
    - Extension - .java 
